<seg id=1> Russian Prime Minister On Economy </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> XINHUA NEWS AGENCY WIRE Moscow, Jan. 8: In today's cabinet session, Russian prime minister Chernomyrdin said that Russia's main accomplishment in 1997 was the creation of the basis for economic growth. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> According to a report from Russian news agency ITAR-Tass, Chernomyrdin said that in comparison with 1996 Russia's total domestic production output grew by 1.2 percent last year, industrial production grew by 3.2 percent, total value of retail products grew by 3.9 percent, and the inflation rate for the year was 11 percent, only half of that of 1996.  Income growth was 2.5 percent. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> At the same time, Chernomyrdin pointed out that there were still quite a few problems in the country last year: the tax collection situation was not good, investment projects weren't completed, the foreign trade surplus decreased, and financial measures enacted by the government didn't work very well. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> In reference to this year's work, Chernomyrdin said that new structural changes and economic growth policies were being drafted up to be submitted to the extended cabinet session for debate on February 26. </seg>
<seg id=6> According to this policy, next year's growth of total domestic production output will be 2 percent, and the inflation rate will decrease to between 8 percent and 5 percent. </seg>
</p>
